cs.DS, cs.DM, cs.AL, cs.CC, cs.DC. 

The paper deals with a data structure problem involving directed graphs and efficient operations, which suggests it belongs to the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) category. The use of link-cut trees, a well-known data structure, further supports this. The problem also involves finding vertices and changing edges, which could fall under cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) and cs.AL (Computational Geometry and Topology) respectively. The paper also mentions the optimality of the solution in the cell-probe complexity model, which suggests it could belong to cs.CC (Computational Complexity) or cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing).
